  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Prayer to the Earth God at the Construction of Yangma Castle
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On [the specified day and month], I, [the undersigned official], hereby report to the Spirit of the Earth.

    Since warfare has not ceased and defense requires constant vigilance, I have commanded the construction of Yangma Castle. Thus I send [these officials] to make this proclamation to the god of this land:

    "Behold, the building of walls and ramparts serves to protect the township. When they are poorly made, the cunning find opportunity to spy; when they are well made, their defense becomes difficult to maintain. Yet now, the howl of wild beasts echoes everywhere and venom spreads on every wind. The people's hearts grow restless, and peace seems impossible to achieve. What land could promise joy in such times? To gain lasting tranquility through brief labor, we must accomplish great works now.

    We have measured the heights and depths, considered the distances near and far, and set all workers to their task. In thirty days, the work is complete. We have given this castle a name that evokes the meaning of horses sheltered in their stalls and those who break through barriers—its position follows the sweep of great clouds and the rise of sheer cliffs. We need not rely on divination, nor do we wait for auspicious signs. The people's hearts were united, and the work proceeded without hardship.

    God, your virtue encompasses all things, and your way flows through humility. Do not refuse the noise of our labor. Grant that this fortress become as strong as gold and as permanent as a moat. Let the sound of our shovels and rammers echo far and wide in joyful triumph. Let the crow-battled walls and falcon-topped ramparts stand high and magnificent. Let the north embrace the moon over the Huai waters and the south drink in the river's mists. Let this fortress shame the fame of iron strongholds and surpass the records of golden bastions. With preparation comes freedom from worry. Hear our prayer, O Spirit."
  footnotes:
    - 'Yangma Castle (羊馬城): Named symbolically—''sheep and horses sheltered'' representing secure defense, and ''breaking barriers'' representing the ability to overcome obstacles.'
    - The poetic imagery of 'crow-battled walls' and 'falcon-topped ramparts' refers to the distinctive architectural features of defensive structures.
    - The Huai waters and river references situate the castle within a specific geographical and spiritual landscape.
    - This is a formal prayer document (祭文) composed by Choe Chi-won, a major literary figure of Unified Silla, blending practical military concern with ornate classical rhetoric.
